Aim: Implement one hot encoding of words or characters. 
Description: One-hot encoding is the most common, most basic way to turn a token into a 
vector. You already saw it in action in our initial IMDB and Reuters examples from chapter 3 
(done with words, in our case). It consists in associating a unique integer index to every 
word, then turning this integer index i into a binary vector of size N, the size of the 
vocabulary, that would be all-zeros except for the i-th entry, which would be 1. 
Of course, one-hot encoding can be done at the character level as well. To unambiguously 
drive home what one-hot encoding is and how to implement it, here are two toy examples of 
one-hot encoding: one for words, the other for characters. 
Program: 
1..One hot encoding for words: 
sentence = "i love machine learning” 
import numpy as np 
words = sentence.split() 
vocab = sorted(set(words)) 
word_to_index = {word: i for i, word in enumerate(vocab)} 
one_hot_vectors = {} 
for word in words: 
vector = np.zeros(len(vocab), dtype=int) 
vector[word_to_index[word]] = 1 
one_hot_vectors[word] = vector 
for word, vec in one_hot_vectors.items(): 
print(word, ":", vec) 
 
Output: 
i : [0 1 0 0] 
love : [0 0 1 0] 
machine : [1 0 0 0] 
learning : [0 0 0 1] 
Roll No:23A91A4449
Exp No: 
Date: 
Page No: 
ADITYA ENGINEERING COLLEGE(A) 
 
 
 
 
2.one hot encoding for characters: 
word = “data" 
import numpy as np 
chars = sorted(set(word)) 
char_to_index = {ch: i for i, ch in enumerate(chars)} 
one_hot_chars = {} 
for ch in word: 
vector = np.zeros(len(chars), dtype=int) 
vector[char_to_index[ch]] = 1 
one_hot_chars[ch] = vector 
for ch, vec in one_hot_chars.items(): 
print(ch, ":", vec) 
 
Output: 
d : [1 0 0 0] 
a : [0 1 0 0] 
t : [0 0 0 1]
